I never write reviews and took the time to do this because the sheer lack of care and negligence I experienced here at Dignity Health Urgent Care. I had a serious infection for which I was prescribed an antibiotic by one of their doctors and told it was important that I start it right away because it would take around 48 hours for it to start decreasing the pain I was experiencing and it could spread to my kidneys. Not only did I write down and select my correct pharmacy in their system (which was less than half a mile down the road on 41st) but the doctor confirmed the address with me again as I was leaving. It was never sent to my pharmacy that day & my pharmacy still didn't have it the following day; also, Dignity Health DOES NOT ANSWER THEIR PHONES AND HAS A FULL VOICEMAIL so you will not hear from them regarding any of your medical concerns unless you physically show up to their office to ask the question and figure out their mistake. IT GETS WORSE. Not only did I have to go to the office to get an answer as to why my prescription was never sent, but when I arrived one of the doctors blamed the other for giving the wrong pharmacy and said he's made several mistakes and then proceeded to give me a sheet of paper with the details for the pharmacy they sent to by mistake & snapped at me when I asked to confirm. The pharmacy they sent me to was BOARDED UP AND CLOSED downtown and had been for weeks. It even showed up as temporarily closed on google. So then I had to do the leg-work of calling this pharmacy to see if they could transfer to an open location (with NO HELP from the doctors at Dignity Health) & I finally got my prescription and started taking it......and when I think my nightmare is finally over with Dignity Health - I get a voicemail from the Doctor 4 days later while I'm at work letting me know he PRESCRIBED THE WRONG ANTIBIOTIC and that I now have to pay for and start an entirely different antibiotic that, again, has been sent to an unknown pharmacy that is likely closed. Again, no way for me to even get more information from this doctor regarding the voicemail, the new medication, or the incorrect pharmacy because he left the same default number to call him back at that DIGNITY HEALTH DOES NOT ANSWER OR ALLOW YOU TO LEAVE VOICEMAILS. I am a frequent traveler and have been to many urgent cares and have never experienced such medical negligence and lack of care in my life. So to the very portly gentleman in the purple shirt with the small beard and bad attitude. If I hadn't respected my family at your establishment I personally would have gave you a clinic on proper work place customer service. I am glad I didn't. Now I believe that I can do what should be the proper method of conversing with someone so naive to a parents dilemma that they put their "my job sucks" manners on display as if saying GET OUT! with your ushered tone. I explained to you that my son is autistic right off the bat, said that he had beaten many games and even though his blank stare and happy grin in your store, the one place he personally asked for by name no less might say otherwise. we went just to get him splatoon 2. I asked if you had it you looked at me then my son an said let me check already knowing that your didn't. With a slow nope, sorry we, are,out. then i asked about mario rabbids you said quickly and confidently itsastrategeygame. I said ok like what kind? you said dude, its an xcom game. like that's really any kind of expanation... Ok i'm not gonna put you down you already do that on a daily basis i'm sure. I also get it your at work your tired and you just wanna go home and relax.I know i work graveyard and am in charge of people, if i dont go in they dont go in and they dont get paid but im not going to talk about how much work has its hard days. I'm going to educate you on an Autistic person let alone a 6 year old child. Autism sounds and even looks crazy but if it works is it really?  Autistic kids learn and do things way differently than normal people on a day to day level but it works, its like you think outside the box all the time and only in black and white but the thing is that they are people like you i'm guessing and me. they like to eat, sing laugh and guess what? play video games, i suggest next time you think someone cant play certain games doesn't mean they can't or dont understand, trust me they do they might even do the same strategy's as you do. I hope we both can say we have learned something from this, i know i have, i learned a bit of patience and to help make more people aware of Autism in our present and future and learn from the past.</review>

< Review>
Solid effort at the soft opening.  Cortado was nice - smooth taste and texture.  Good coffee.  The mocha is light on the chocolate and a little more of a vanilla note, but still definitely a 'mocha.' At least, that was my initial take - I'll try it again next time and see if maybe I've gotten too used to unsweetened mochas with cayenne . The space is amazing - lots of seats.  Couches, bar seating at the window, group tables....  Staff is friendly.  I talked briefly to the managers/owners/directors - the place is setup as a non profit and will be donating to local charities.  Sounds like a great way to work with the community.  Hope they keep up the good work.</Review>

< Review>
I would come to this place for the baked goods alone. The cheese waffle came warm, and it was the perfect toasted outside with a chewy inside. Reminded me a lot of Fogo de Chao's cheesy bread if you've ever had it. The cookie was served cold but somehow perfectly crispy on the outside and gooey on the inside. It was coated with sugar but had strong gingerbread flavor - what I'd imagine I'd be eating on a Christmas morning!

I don't normally like sweet coffees so I was a bit nervous about the marshmallow latte but found it was perfect. Vietnamese coffee wasn't authentic vietnamese style, tasted more like a cold brew with condensed milk but I wasn't disappointed. Only tiny con was the portion was smaller than expected.

I love that they have a "Surprise Me!" menu item. It's just so fun and I haven't seen this at other shops.

Overall will be going back and sharing with my family & friends!< /Review>

< date>
1567115895576</date>
< Resp>
None<//Resp>
< text>
Visited here on a weekday morning and it was easy to find parking and no line for service. Place is BIG (by other Bay Area coffee shops save for Equator in SF), and plenty of seating was available (probably 15 customers at the time).

I ordered their single origin espresso, which was served on a nice wooden tray including a spoon to stir and sparkling water to cleanse palate. Very tasty, although slightly too fruity for my preference with espresso. I also had a pour over of their Kenyan single origin, and unfortunately it was not great. There was a strong vegetal flavor that wasn't enjoyable - whether that was the roast (somewhat doubtful due to using the highly reputable Counter Culture's beans) or the brew, I'm not sure. The finish was good, clean and wet, and the mug had a lovely big handle. Will have to try another pour over in the future as their drip that my friend had was very good, and the espresso was also of a high standard.

My only other complaint was that it was too quiet - it felt like we had to whisper or we'd be the crazy loud obnoxious ones. Just about everybody else there was working, so there wasn't much general conversational noise, but the music was also very low. Not a big deal, and would be easily remedied.<//text>

<date>1561154663214<//date><Rating>2</Rating>< text>
Strong cappuccino, average-looking pastries, large space with mock fireplace. This cafe is on the premises of a church and has received nonprofit status, meaning it does not pay the same taxes as a Starbucks down the street.

The cafe says it does not pay rent, which allows it to function better and perhaps one day offer a percentage of profits to a local school (Rosemary was the name I was given).

The cafe‚Äôs staff also claims it‚Äôs able to offer cheaper prices for ‚Äúorganic‚Äù products, but my personal understanding of taxation led me to search for some public benefit different from a Starbucks... and I couldn‚Äôt find one after speaking to two different staff members. I know rich people have lawyers to minimize taxes (look up Panama Papers) but when others decide they want to stretch tax laws, I suppose the line gets more and more blurry until it disappears.

If you like your coffee strong but your tax enforcement Balkanized, check out this cafe. (June 2019)< /text>

The Ladies here are amazing!!!

I suffer from mental abilities, that's right abilities. Their only disabilities if you let them limit you. 1 of them is anxiety believe it or not and I was sooo nervous I thought i would pass out on my way to my stylist chair. And I'm horrible with names so I'm sooo sorry I don't remember any of their names, I'm truly sorry.

< Review>
Visited this beautiful winery with my friend who is a member here and had an amazing time. Although it was off-season in Napa, we were welcomed with a very pretty and colorful wall of ivy, along with a glass of their unfiltered Chardonnay. The tasting room was modern and chic and was a great atmosphere. Our host Sean was knowledgeable about the wine, grapes, and more. He also gave us a tour to learn more about the fermentation process and barrels, which was very interesting. The winds were AMAZING and my favorite was the Three Graces.< /Review>

Have been drinking their wines for years. First time visiting the vineyard. This is a beautiful facility! Friendly staff, great atmosphere, and their wines are delicious. < review>
Hands-down, the highlight of our day -- Clos du Val offered a personalized experience, starting with a custom-printed reservation card for our table, which we were shown to by a welcoming and attentive staff.  We enjoyed our wine tasting at a relaxed pace on a beautiful sunny patio.  We noticed that a nearby table had a more aggressive agenda, which CdV honored to make sure that the party could make their next appointment.

The wine punches above its weight--it is competitive with bottles nearly twice the price; perhaps being an original Napa winery before the famous "Paris Tasting" transformed the valley explains why!<//review>

<user_id>101220706149966390072<//user_id><user_name>Sherry Li<//user_name><Time>1379446755934</Time>< Rating>
3< /Rating>
< text>
Clos Du Val is nestled in the heart of Stags Leap district - one of my favorite areas in Napa to wine taste. As you walk in, you see several canopied seating areas that are marked "reserved". As we found out very soon thereafter, they're reserved for club members, which is a definite perk for becoming a member because it's a delightful set up for an afternoon wine tasting.

Our server was very nice and verbose. He explained the history of the winery and the style of wines that they make. They have several chardonnays, pinot noirs and cabernet sauvignons. I personally don't like the style of Clos Du Val wines as they are very French. I prefer California style. But the wines here are very well made and definitely worth a taste.< /text>
